      "section": "full_prompt",
      "index": 0,
      "text": "Edit the input image as a 老旧厂房 innovation-community case.\n\nScene-graph removals:\n- vehicle_area (car/vehicle): reduce dominant parked or service vehicles and reconstruct a slow, pedestrian-first innovation-community edge.\n- closed_boundary (wall/fence): soften the closed boundary and selectively open it as an accessible innovation-community interface.\n- inactive_factory_facade: reduce blank, sealed, or purely storage-like facade behavior while preserving industrial texture and existing geometry.\n\nScene-graph additions:\n- maker_lab_frontage (transparent maker lab): add a realistic visible maker/co-working interior connected to existing building, wall, door, or window edges.\n- prototype_display (prototype display wall): add one realistic display zone with abstract diagrams, small models, or material samples anchored to a wall/building frontage or public node.\n- collaboration_seating (modular bench/worktable): add realistic modular seating and a worktable near existing trees, sidewalk, entrance, or public edge.\n- smart_bench (charging smart bench): add one realistic smart bench with subtle charging details near a public path or shaded edge.\n- rain_garden (native rain-garden planting): add native planting that links tree/plant nodes to seating and stormwater edge.\n- micro_mobility_dock (bike/scooter dock): add a compact micro-mobility dock at the street, entrance, or public-space edge without blocking circulation.\n- community_screen (interactive community screen): add one restrained screen or panel with abstract graphics only, supporting prototype discussion and public information.\n- facade_depth_system (3D facade/spatial interface): use wall thickness, doorway depth, canopy, window reveal, platform edge, and ground-plane connection to make the update read as a real three-dimensional spatial scene.\n- adaptive_reuse_facade (factory facade activation): add realistic transparent or semi-transparent maker/coworking frontage attached to the existing factory wall, door, or window line.\n- industrial_wall_display (prototype/material wall): convert part of the existing wall or facade into a restrained prototype display and material sample interface, without fake readable text.\n- three_dimensional_threshold (canopy/porch/entrance depth): add a physically buildable semi-outdoor entrance porch, shallow canopy, or recessed workspace edge that shows depth from ground to facade.\n- visible_maker_interior (inside-outside connection): reveal a modest maker lab or shared studio behind existing openings, keeping the original industrial structure legible.\n\nPattern-guided instructions:\n- Weaken negative active relation `building - street - sidewalk` by changing the node relationship toward old industrial factory adaptive reuse: facade activation, wall/interface renovation, 3D semi-outdoor threshold, visible maker/co-working interior, prototype display frontage, and preserved industrial character.\n- Treat building, wall, door, window, roof edge, and ground plane as editable 3D spatial carriers: activate the facade without flattening it into a poster.\n- Prioritize adaptive reuse: visible maker lab, workshop frontage, prototype display wall, semi-outdoor entrance porch, and preserved industrial material traces.\n- Function-specific focus: old industrial factory adaptive reuse: facade activation, wall/interface renovation, 3D semi-outdoor threshold, visible maker/co-working interior, prototype display frontage, and preserved industrial character; building / facade / door / window / wall relations should become transparent maker-lab frontage, open innovation studio, and prototype display interface; street / sidewalk relations should become a slow public threshold with micro-mobility, collaboration seating, and visible community activity; closed boundary relations should become a permeable innovation-community porch, entrance, or display window.\n- Make the update clearly about learning, making, prototyping, co-working, public demonstration, and community collaboration.\nFunction-specific avoidances:\n- do not turn the factory into a generic shopping street or decorative facade\n- do not erase old industrial texture; keep brick/concrete/steel traces where present\n\nFinal constraints:\n- Preserve the original camera viewpoint, perspective, major building geometry, street/yard layout, trees, and site identity.\n- Keep the result photorealistic and physically buildable as a real street, factory-edge, or public-space scene, not a staged render.\n- Make building facade, wall surface, entrance depth, canopy, ground plane, and open-space furniture read as a coherent 3D spatial system where relevant.\n- Keep the exact original image viewpoint and framing; do not rotate, zoom, crop differently, or change the camera height/lens feeling.\n- Do not add decorative lighting, warm ambient lighting, glowing light strips, or night-scene effects. If lighting is adjusted, only use realistic neutral white daylight/white functional light and minor brightness correction.\n- Use refined steel, glass, warm timber, robust paving, native planting, and believable human activity without weakening the real street-scene feeling.\n- Use icon-only wayfinding and abstract display graphics; no readable text, no logos, no fake words.\n- Avoid fantasy architecture, generic beautification, excessive cars, empty-plaza feeling, and changes unrelated to innovation-community use."
    }
